    <article class="blog-content">
        <header class="blog-header">
            <h1>You don’t have the time to read <span style='font-size:20px;'>&#8987;</span> </h1>
            <div class="blog-meta">
                Published on <time datetime="2025-01-19">January 19, 2025</time>
            </div>
        </header>

        <div class="blog-body">
            <!-- Your blog post content goes here -->
            <p><p>Seriously? Your brain just made you believe that? </p>

<p>99% of the time in our life - “I don’t have time to read” is a big lie that our brain makes us believe in. </p>

<p>Our brain loves the dopamine, serotonin and all the fancy chemicals it gets by the things that we do. (nowadays, we subconsciously do) </p>

<p>Now, I won’t write about most of the things but the biggest culprit that makes our brain happy in the short term which make our brain capable enough to convince us that we really love to do it - yes, yes, we all know what it is, so here you go - the star of the show “Scrolling”. </p>

<p>We scroll the fu*k out of our time almost on most of the days - and spend time in other similar activities that eats up our time without even realizing that how much time has passed. A simple way to find this is to check our daily screentime. 3hrs, 4hrs sometimes 5-6 or even 7hrs and then we say “oh, I don’t have time to read”. </p>

<p>I think we really need to take a step back and think whenever we say this - to put things in perspective, let’s say even if you don’t want to read, think about the work, hobby, activity or any other thing that you like - you can do if you just reduce your overall screentime.  </p>

          
        </div>

